Setting Up kubernetes dashboards using Headlamp

In-cluster | Headlamp
In-cluster | Headlamp
A common use case for any Kubernetes web UI is to deploy it in-cluster and
helm repo add headlamp https://kubernetes-sigs.github.io/headlamp/
helm install my-headlamp headlamp/headlamp --namespace kube-system
kubectl get svc -n kube-system
kubectl edit svc my-headlamp -n kube-system
change service type to NodePort
access it with public-ip:port no
kubectl create token my-headlamp --namespace kube-system
run this to get token
 
GIT
git branching strategies
git branch production rules:
A branch production rule is a set of rules or policies that define how the production branch is used, protected, and updated in Git.
In most teams, the production branch is called main or master, and it represents live, deployable code.
Production branch rules answer this question:
“What is allowed and not allowed on the production branch?”
These rules are enforced to:
Prevent accidental outages
Maintain stability
Ensure quality and security

✅ All changes must come through:

Pull Requests (PRs)
Merge Requests (MRs)

Before merging into production:

✅ Code review is mandatory
✅ Usually 1–2 approvals required

Only allow merge if:

✅ Build succeeds
✅ Tests pass
✅ Linting/security scans pass

Production branch must always be in a releasable state
This means:
No broken code
No half‑finished features
Feature flags for incomplete work

Limited Who Can Merge
Only:
Senior developers
Tech leads
DevOps engineers

If production breaks:
Create a hotfix/* branch from main
Fix the issue
Merge back into main (and develop if used)
